{"accepted":[{"assertion":"Formal-Conjectures statement: Erdos354.erdos_354.parts.i https://google-deepmind.github.io/formal-conjectures/theorem/?name=Erdos354.erdos_354.parts.i.","id":"vf_1c6862ad75773c7c","trust":"signed","type":"theoretical"},{"assertion":"Erdős Problem #354: declared status 'open'. Formalized: yes. Let $\\alpha,\\beta\\in \\mathbb{R}_{>0}$ such that $\\alpha/\\beta$ is irrational. Is the multiset\\[\\{ \\lfloor \\alpha\\rfloor,\\lfloor 2\\alpha\\rfloor,\\lfloor 4\\alpha\\rfloor,\\ldots\\}\\cup \\{ \\lfloor \\beta\\rfloor,\\lfloor 2\\beta\\rfloor,\\lfloor 4\\beta\\rfloor,\\ldots\\}\\]complete? That is, can all sufficiently large natural numbers $n$ be written as\\[n=\\sum_{s\\in S}\\lfloor 2^s\\alpha\\rfloor+\\sum_{t\\in T}\\lfloor 2^t\\beta\\rfloor\\]for some finite $S,T\\subset \\mathbb{N}$?\n\nWhat if $2$ is replaced by some $\\gamma\\in(1,2)$? Current best: Hegyv\\'{a}ri \\cite{He89} proved that the sequence is not complete if $\\alpha\\geq 2$ and $\\beta =2^k\\alpha$ for some $k\\geq 0$. Prize: no. Tags: number theory.","id":"vf_292d7ad79b021a64","trust":"signed","type":"theoretical"}],"accepted_activity":false,"activity":[],"activity_types":[],"attempt_count":0,"banked_attempt_count":0,"commits":[],"dependency_impact":"none","detail_url":"problems/354.json","draft_proposals":[],"edges":[{"evidence":"Problem identity derived from the accepted finding's pinned source anchor.","inferred":true,"relation":"describes","source":"vf_1c6862ad75773c7c","source_root":"sha256:1faedc24f040a60a22177b456c74b969a61ce8836082297b1835797a57b4fa56","target":"erdos:354","trust":"signed"},{"evidence":"Materialized typed link between accepted findings.","inferred":true,"relation":"synthesized_from","source":"vf_1c6862ad75773c7c","source_root":"sha256:1faedc24f040a60a22177b456c74b969a61ce8836082297b1835797a57b4fa56","target":"vf_292d7ad79b021a64","trust":"signed"},{"evidence":"Problem identity derived from the accepted finding's pinned source anchor.","inferred":t